# Development Workflow

## Environment Variables

```env
# .env (never commit this file)
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://admin:admin@localhost:5432/resource_planner?schema=public

JIRA_HOST=https://your-company.atlassian.net
JIRA_EMAIL=your.email@company.be
JIRA_TOKEN=your_api_token_from_jira_profile
JIRA_FILTER_ID=12345
```

`src/generated/prisma/` is gitignored. It is rebuilt by `npm install` via the `postinstall`
hook (`prisma generate`).

## Daily Startup

```bash
docker start resource-planner-db   # skip if restart:always is set
cd ~/projects/resource-planner
nvm use                            # uses .nvmrc (Node >= 20.19 required by Prisma/tooling)
npm run db:migrate                 # apply any pending migrations
npm run dev                        # → http://localhost:3000
```

## After Schema Changes

```bash
npx prisma migrate dev   # local: apply migration + regenerate client
npx prisma generate      # if only the client is stale (no new migration)
rm -rf .next             # clear Turbopack cache
npm run dev
```

If the dev server errors with a stale table name (e.g. `public.product` instead of
`allocation_entity`), delete `.next/` and restart — Turbopack will pick up the regenerated
Prisma client.

## Full Production Seed — Correct Order

```bash
npm run db:migrate            # prisma migrate deploy
npm run db:seed:eotp          # upsert eotp_definition from EOTP-Budget-Owner.csv (canonical EOTP catalog)
npm run db:seed:products      # upsert allocation_entity from PRODUCTS.csv + link eotp_definition_id
npm run db:seed:prod          # resources, rates, initiatives, allocations + recreate views
npm run db:seed:routing       # optional: seed eotp_routing from EOTP_ROUTING.csv (sets eotp_definition_id)
npm run db:backfill:eotp-routing-fks  # optional: re-link eotp_routing.eotp_definition_id if catalog was seeded late
```

## Production Seed Flags

| Command | Effect |
|---|---|
| `npm run db:seed:prod` | Upsert only — existing rows not in CSV are left untouched |
| `SEED_PROD_RESET=1 npm run db:seed:prod` | Clears planner tables (allocations, rates, initiatives, resources) — **preserves** `allocation_entity` |
| `SEED_VIEW_ONLY=1 npm run db:seed:prod` | Recreates `v_allocation_costs` + `v_eotp_costs` only — no CSV import |
| `npm run db:recreate:eotp-costs` | Recreates `v_eotp_costs` only (requires `v_allocation_costs` to exist) |

## Make Postgres Survive Reboots

```bash
docker update --restart always resource-planner-db
```

Combined with Docker Desktop set to start on Windows login, no manual DB startup is ever needed.

